ğŸ Python Data Types and Print Statements

ğŸ“¦ Data Types

Python provides several built-in data types, grouped into the following categories:

1.Text Type: str

2.Numeric Types: int, float, complex

3.Sequence Types: list, tuple, range

4.Mapping Type: dict

5.Set Types: set, frozenset

6.Boolean Type: bool

7.Binary Types: bytes, bytearray, memoryview

8.None Type: NoneType



---

ğŸ“ Text Data Type

1.String (str)

Represents a sequence of characters

Enclosed in single, double, or triple quotes


name = "John"


---

ğŸ”¢ Numeric Data Types

1.Integer (int)

Represents whole numbers


a = 10
b = -5

2.Float (float)

Represents decimal or floating-point values


x = 3.14
y = -2.5

3.Complex (complex)

Represents complex numbers


c = 3 + 4j


---

ğŸ“š Sequence Data Types

1.Tuple

Ordered

Immutable (cannot be changed)

Enclosed in parentheses ()


t = (1, 2, 3)

2.List

Ordered

Mutable (can be changed)

Enclosed in square brackets []


l = [1, 2, 3]


---

ğŸ—‚ Mapping Data Type

1.Dictionary (dict)

Stores data in key-value pairs

Enclosed in curly braces {}


student = {
    "name": "John",
    "age": 30
}


---

ğŸ”¹ Set Data Types

1.Set

Unordered collection

Stores unique elements


s = {1, 2, 3}


---

ğŸ” Boolean Data Type

1.Boolean (bool)

Represents logical values

Can be either True or False

Used in conditions and control flow


is_active = True


---

ğŸš« None Data Type

1.None

Represents the absence of a value

Similar to a null value


result = None


---

ğŸ–¨ Print Statements in Python

Different ways to print output in Python:

1ï¸âƒ£ Using comma ,

Adds a space automatically.

print("Age is", 25)

2ï¸âƒ£ Using +

Used for string concatenation.

print("Age is " + "25")

3ï¸âƒ£ Using format specifiers

print("Age is %d" % 25)

4ï¸âƒ£ Using f-strings

age = 25
print(f"Age is {age}")
